(31, 2, '2019-02-12 15:00:07', '2019-02-12 15:00:07', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	As <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/10-best-smartphones/\">phones</a> become more sophisticated and mature, choosing one brand over another is increasingly hard. Is <a href=\"https://www.apple.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Apple</a> really better than <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/topic/samsung/\">Samsung</a>, or is <a href=\"https://www.samsung.com/us/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Samsung</a> the top phone maker?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>\n		top picks\n	</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2017/04/04/4aea62a3-43a3-4909-ae31-c3953dac6f12/resize/220x165/424bd1414aa9fb5bf1d47e7468b05155/samsung-galaxy-s8-hidden-features-009.jpg\" alt=\"The 10 best smartphones right now\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n                    <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/10-best-smartphones/\">\n                        The 10 best smartphones right now\n                    </a>\n                </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It\'s easy to find a great \nphone today. In fact, current flagship devices are so good you really \ndon\'t need to be replacing them every year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n                <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/10-best-smartphones/\">Read More</a>\n            </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	Selecting the right phone for you depends on several factors:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	<strong>Must read: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-to-decide-picking-the-2018-iphone-thats-right-for-you/\">How to decide: Picking the 2018 iPhone that\'s right for you</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	Do you prefer a large screen or small? Are you super picky about pictures the camera takes and do you <a href=\"https://shuttermuse.com/glossary/pixel-peeper/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">pixel-peep</a>\n your photos seeking technical perfection? Do you play processor- or \ngraphics-intensive games or mostly browse the web, make calls, and watch\n an occasional movie? Do you need to store a terabyte of data or is less\n storage okay? How much are you willing to pay to own the latest and \ngreatest device?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	With these questions in mind, I took a comparative look at the latest <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/topic/apple/\">Apple</a> and Samsung devices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	Apple\'s line-up includes the new <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/new-2018-iphone-iphone-x-plus-iphone-9-heres-what-we-know/\">iPhone</a> XS, and iPhone XS Max. Likewise, Samsung offers the Galaxy S9, S9+, and Note 9.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	The primary differences between the Apple phones \nare screen size and battery life (the XS Max has a larger screen and \nsomewhat bigger battery). The S9 approximately matches the iPhone XS in \nsize, while the S9+ corresponds roughly to the <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/meet-apples-iphone-xs-iphone-xs-max-and-iphone-xr-prices-and-specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iPhone XS Max</a>.\n The Note 9 is also large but adds a pen for writing on the screen. Each\n phone variant has minor other differences in the specifications, but \noverall that\'s the general description.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	<strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/galaxy-note-9-or-iphone-XS-max-compare-before-you-upgrade/\">Galaxy Note 9 or iPhone XS Max? Compare before you upgrade</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Physical size</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 	The most obvious difference between these phones is size. This table\n summarizes the size and screen resolution of each phone:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong><a href=\"https://www.apple.com/iphone-XS/specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iPhone XS:</a></strong> 5.8-inch screen size, 2436 x 1125 resolution</li><li><strong><a href=\"https://www.apple.com/iphone-XS/specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iPhone XS Max:</a></strong> 6.5-inch screen size, 2688 x 1242 resolution</li><li><strong><a href=\"https://www.samsung.com/us/smartphones/galaxy-s9/specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Samsung S9: </a></strong>5.8-inch screen size, 2960 x 1440 resolution</li><li><strong><a href=\"https://www.samsung.com/us/smartphones/galaxy-s9/specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Samsung S9+:</a></strong> 6.2-inch screen size, 2960 x 1440 resolution</li><li><strong><a href=\"https://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/galaxy-note9/specs/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Samsung Note 9:</a></strong> 6.4-inch screen size, 2960 x 1440 resolution</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 	Screen size has an impact on many aspects of these phones. The \ndecision to use a smaller or larger phone is highly personal, depending \non factors such as portability, hand size, and eyesight.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	Here are positive aspects of a larger screen:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Everything on the screen is bigger and easier to read.</li><li>Larger keyboards offer more space for fat fingers when typing.</li><li>Movies and photos look beautiful.</li><li>Samsung\n lets you multitask apps in multiple windows. This software trick is \ngreat for viewing your calendar while sending an email, as one small \nexample. Apple lags when it comes to making use of the large screen.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	There are also downsides to a larger phone:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Larger phones do not fit easily into pockets.</li><li>The large size phones are easier to drop and break. Give the cost of screen repairs, this is a real consideration.</li><li>They are heavier and feel less convenient in hand.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 	Although screen resolutions and phone sizes are different between \nSamsung and Apple, in practice, the small and large variants from each \ncompany do match fairly closely. The iPhone XS Max is a bit wider and \nheavier than either the <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/product/samsung-galaxy-s9-plus/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Samsung Galaxy S9+</a> and the Note 8 marginally easier to handle than the XS Max.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/product/samsung-galaxy-note-9/\">Samsung Galaxy Note 9 review: Big battery and superb S Pen experience power productivity</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	Some will say that the Note 9 doesn\'t offer much over the <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/product/samsung-galaxy-note8-sm-n950u-midnight-black-4g-lte-64-gb-gsm-smartphone/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Note 8</a>,\n but those who use their phones to get work done with greatly appreciate\n the massive 4,000 mAh battery, Bluetooth S Pen, stunning display, \nvirtually unlimited storage options, and more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	If you want a \nsmaller phone, get the iPhone XS or the Galaxy S9. If you prefer \nsomething big, either the XS Max or the larger Samsung devices are for \nyou. Small differences in phone specifications have little impact on \ndaily use, so don\'t worry about them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	<strong>Summary:</strong> \nAlthough sizes are roughly comparable, Samsung takes advantage of the \nlarge screen, through multitasking, in a way that Apple does not.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	<strong>Winner:</strong> Tie on the small phones, but Samsung wins on the larger size.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Camera</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	For most people taking casual snapshots, both Samsung and Apple offer <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-to-take-your-smartphone-photos-to-the-next-level/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">photo quality</a>\n that is good enough to replace a dedicated camera. That said, each \ncompany has strengths and weaknesses when it comes to photos and video.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 	In general, Samsung\'s telephoto lens (these phones have two lenses, \none wide-angle and other for distance), while the new Apple phones have \nbetter dynamic range. However, in some cases, Apple\'s dynamic range \ncomes at the expense of flattening the visual tone and contrast of \nimages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	This image, taken from a video created by <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WTg6ZYpvbo\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">SuperSaf TV</a>, demonstrates the importance of dynamic range. Note this image is part of a video test, but it shows off dynamic range nicely.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet4.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/2018/09/24/754bf1e1-4424-4be0-a698-7f40c7013ddf/c9ee0d97e37c2feaa0e4c9544b1ae796/dynamic-range.jpg\" alt=\"Dynamic range compared\" /><figcaption>Dynamic range compare - iPhone X Max vs Samsung Galaxy Note 9. Photo from <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WTg6ZYpvbo\">SuperSaf TV</a> on YouTube. </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>\n		Featured stories\n	</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/top-cloud-providers-2019-aws-microsoft-azure-google-cloud-ibm-makes-hybrid-move-salesforce-dominates-saas/\">Top cloud providers 2019: AWS, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud; IBM makes hybrid move; Salesforce dominates SaaS</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/good-enough-5g-fixed-wireless-broadband-could-change-everything/\">Good enough 5G fixed-wireless broadband could change everything</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/russia-to-disconnect-from-the-internet-as-part-of-a-planned-test/\">Russia to disconnect from the internet as part of a planned test</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/an-apple-store-salesman-questioned-my-intelligence-says-customer/\">An Apple store salesman questioned my intelligence, says customer</a>\n                    </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 With the Samsung, \nthe sky is completely over-exposed with no cloud detail at all; the \nApple phone retains color in the trees, with less overall contrast, \nwhile the clouds are visible in the bright sky. Although it\'s not clear \nwhether Apple achieves this dynamic range with a better sensor or \nthrough more sophisticated manipulation of brightness curves, the iPhone\n XS is better.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 On the other hand, <a href=\"https://www.tomsguide.com/us/iphone-XS-vs-galaxy-note-9-camera,review-5766.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><em>Tom\'s Guide</em></a>\n took photos with the iPhone XS and Galaxy S9. The iPhone XS versions \nare flat and lifeless while the Note 9 photos are brighter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Portrait mode on these phones uses <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_photography\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">computational photography</a> techniques to adjust the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bokeh\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">bokeh</a>,\n or background blur, of photos. The resulting image, therefore, results \nfrom hardware capture together with software processing. As users, we \nonly care about the result, but it\'s helpful to be aware of what\'s \nhappening behind the scenes inside these devices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-the-iphone-lost-its-crown-to-the-apple-watch/\">How the iPhone lost its crown to the Apple Watch</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 The new iPhones include a larger <a href=\"https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+XS++and+XS+Max+Teardown/113021#s216143\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">sensor</a>\n that gathers light more effectively than in the past. As a result, the \nlow-light performance of the XS series has improved over the original \niPhone X. However, the Samsung devices have a larger <a href=\"https://www.androidauthority.com/what-is-aperture-789927/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">aperture</a>, so they allow more light into the sensor, which significantly improves photos taken in low light.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 If you want to see comparison photos, check this <a href=\"https://mashable.com/feature/apple-iphone-XS-max-review/#OpNvbMW7.aqy\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">article</a>, which does an excellent job showing side-by-side photos from Apple, Samsung, and Google flagship phones.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Photo analyst Ken Rockwell has an excellent article praising the iPhone XS Max <a href=\"https://kenrockwell.com/tech/comparisons/iphone-vs-full-frame-bokeh.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">depth of field</a> and bokeh simulation while comparing it to a full-frame DSLR.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong>\n The iPhone XS offers significant camera improvement over last year\'s \niPhone X. However, the Samsung devices continue to hold their own. \nDepending on what you are photographing, either phone may give superior \nresults to the other, and you cannot go wrong either way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Tie</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Speed</strong> </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 When evaluating speed for general business purposes, the most \nimportant criteria is subjective: Does the phone feel fast enough for \nyou?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-secretly-logs-users-into-chrome-whenever-they-log-into-a-google-site/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Browsing websites</a>,\n writing documents, watching movies, listening to music, using \nspreadsheets, and similar activities do not require the fastest speeds, \nwhether on desktop computers or mobile devices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/expect-ho-hum-iteration-not-innovation-from-next-weeks-upcoming-apple-event-and-yet/\">The big yawn: These new iPhones will be so boring, I can\'t wait</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 On the other hand, editing movies and playing action games do gain \nreal benefits from faster processor and graphics speeds. So, if you \ncreate movies or want to squeeze the highest possible frame rates out of\n games and simulations, then speed is important. Otherwise, not so much.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Just for kicks, I benchmarked the iPhone XS and the Galaxy S9+ using the popular <a href=\"http://www.antutu.com/en/index.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Antutu</a> test software. Antutu runs a variety of tests to gauge the speed of multiple subsystems on a mobile device.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 As you can see from the results below, the iPhone comes out significantly ahead on all scores:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/2018/09/25/95d4e4c1-64a9-4ebb-b853-ec6394636420/c43d50aa3518ff4bde6e9742c9bd1b82/antutu-scores.jpg\" alt=\"Antutu scores\" /><figcaption>Antutu benchmark scores </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 But, what do these <a href=\"https://lifehacker.com/the-differences-between-synthetic-real-world-and-hybr-1663435313\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">synthetic</a> benchmarks tell us that\'s useful? In short, not much beyond the fact that Apple runs faster hardware than Samsung.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>\n		More Apple\n	</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-cuts-q1-revenue-outlook-due-to-weak-iphone-sales-chinese-market/\">Apple cuts Q1 revenue outlook</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/apples-q1-revenue-miss-here-are-the-5-takeaways-you-need-to-know/\">The 5 takeaways you need to know</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/bad-news-for-apple-will-be-good-news-for-apple-buyers/\">Bad news for Apple will be good news for Apple buyers</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/apples-iphone-xr-bad-marketing-or-sneakily-clever/\">iPhone XR: Bad marketing or sneakily clever?</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/hey-apple-forget-airpower-get-your-accessories-act-together/\">Hey Apple: Forget AirPower. Get your accessories act together</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/five-major-challenges-facing-apple-in-2019/\">Five major challenges facing Apple in 2019</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/apples-biggest-embarrassment-of-2018/\">Apple\'s biggest embarrassment of 2018</a>\n                    </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Eventually, \naugmented reality and all kinds of AI applications will make use of that\n fancy hardware, but that time is not yet here for most of us.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Let your own subjective experience be a guide. If your phone feels responsive and fast when you open apps, browse the web, <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-expect-email-from-us-on-our-new-policy-on-harvesting-your-personal-data/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">send email</a>,\n or watch a movie, then it\'s probably fast enough for your needs. Of \ncourse, you can pay more to gain additional snappy responsiveness, but \nonly you can decide if the cost is worth the benefit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong> Even though it makes no practical difference for most users, the new iPhones are faster than Samsung\'s latest offerings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Apple</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Screen quality</strong> </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Samsung and Apple use fabulous OLED screens on their phones. You cannot go wrong with either. Check the great review of the <a href=\"http://www.displaymate.com/Galaxy_Note9_ShootOut_44N9.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Note 9</a> screen from DisplayMate. <a href=\"http://www.displaymate.com/iPhoneXS_ShootOut_1s.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">And here is their review of the iPhone XS Max screen.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong> Both companies use bright, sharp, highly-calibrated screens.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Tie</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Home screen unlocking</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 Fast, reliable phone unlocking is a crucial feature in today\'s \nsecurity-conscious world. Our phones store financial data, business \ninformation, and all kinds of personal content, so security is a crucial\n dimension when evaluating mobile devices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Face ID was one of \nthe great innovations on last year\'s iPhone X. Although the original \nincarnation of Face ID worked well most of the time, Face ID on the new \niPhones is faster and more reliable than in the past. As you use <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-wants-you-to-stop-remembering-passwords/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Face ID</a>, it becomes a natural way to unlock the phone: simply look at the screen and it unlocks almost immediately.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.cnet.com/how-to/ios-12-release-date-new-features-hidden-features/?ftag=CMG-01-10aaa1b\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">iOS 12: Release date, new features, and hidden features</a> CNET</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 The Samsung devices offer facial recognition, iris scanning and a \nfingerprint sensor to unlock the phone. Of these three, I found the \nfingerprint sensor to be fast and reliable, while the other methods seem\n slow and often do not work at all.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong> \nSecurity combined with speed and ease of use is the holy grail of home \nscreen unlocked. Apple does this better than anyone and leaves Samsung \nin the dust on this point.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Apple</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Storage capacity</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 Depending on your needs, you may want lots of storage space. For \nexample, if you want to store many high-res movies, then you will \nrequire more space than someone who does not watch movies on their \nphone.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Samsung phones come with a MicroSD card expansion slot, \nwhich lets you increase storage capacity beyond what is built into the \nphone. The top storage option from Samsung is the 512GB version of the \nNote 9, which can expand to 1TB with a 512GB <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/future-sd-cards-expect-monster-128tb-storage-plus-zippier-data-transfers/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">MicroSD card</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.techrepublic.com/pictures/photos-best-smartphones-of-2018-for-tech-experts/?ftag=CMG-01-10aaa1b\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Best smartphones of 2018 for tech experts</a> TechRepublic</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 The Apple phones max out at 512GB of internal storage that is not expandable.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong> If you need 1TB of data storage, go with Samsung. Otherwise, both companies offer good options, but they are expensive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Samsung</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Password management</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 As the need for strong, unique passwords grows, the complexity and \nhassle of remembering those passwords also increase. Password managers, \nsuch as <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/lastpass-hit-by-password-stealing-and-code-execution-vulnerabilities/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">LastPass </a>and\n Dashlane, help you create a unique and strong password for every \nwebsite. The password manager then automatically supplies those \ncredentials when logging into websites and apps.<a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/pictures/mobile-phone-memory-lane-what-was-your-first-device/\">Mobile phone memory lane: What was your first...</a><a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/pictures/mobile-phone-memory-lane-what-was-your-first-device/\">SEE FULL GALLERY</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/03/02/7d1d518f-6de4-480a-966d-d5a0bc87e961/thumbnail/170x128/bebaddfb7330e8b8c3974dd09f409dde/our-first-cell-phones.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/112ea539-4820-44a0-a331-ce50de93ad34/thumbnail/170x128/f4961127e4c53c9b4655fc9d8f90e0cb/matt-miller.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/6e60ba4a-0f8a-4451-8af3-b68924abfafd/thumbnail/170x128/5ecc42b770cdd44f98bf7ba5afcc4dac/charlie.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/0d17dfc3-be6c-4163-97a5-d1185b98d196/thumbnail/170x128/f1bd3ff3e9011ca4ec20db75e49b3317/cipriani.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/6fcbf7f5-b9ce-4b5a-a86a-b450d9d4f843/thumbnail/170x128/d7380c088aac0299c14673522d21302d/adrian.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/1bcd8c0d-b82d-4d57-8db3-7abe49573574/thumbnail/170x128/a164091860d1e7809645c11ecaa7fe19/corinne-reichert.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/7829b5c6-bcef-4438-8d25-46141574bf97/thumbnail/170x128/12465eba3ddcdf7ef9805994976890aa/grober.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet4.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/5a633478-07bc-4f22-8e51-6bc7f43d03d5/thumbnail/170x128/f676f90a7903426b87ddeb71818207db/ed-bott-no-phone.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/1baf6f68-1bda-4e9c-999b-1320d9bc3095/thumbnail/170x128/12969592b99a86198c817970b39473c5/asha.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet4.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2018/02/28/668f4b24-ce11-4fb2-9e97-2779822c86dd/thumbnail/170x128/6a8d8dea49bc4d8ae25598a0ecadc7cb/perlow-star-tac.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":23} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-23\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":24} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-1.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-24\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-3.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":26} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-2.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-26\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":30} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-7.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-30\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":27} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-4.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-27\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":28} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-5.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-28\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":29} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://localhost/Techthirstie/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image-6.gif\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-29\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n                                                                    \n                            \n                                            \n                \n\n                \n                                        1 - 5 of 18\n\n                    \n                        <a>\n                            NEXT     </a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Historically, using a password manager on both Android and iOS has been a complicated, unreliable, and hard to use mess.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/should-i-install-ios-12-on-my-old-iphone-or-ipad/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">With the new iOS 12</a>,\n Apple has significantly improved the integration of password managers \nto the point where they are convenient and safe to use. Although this is\n an operating system issue rather than a function of hardware, it is of \nenough importance to warrant being called out here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong> Password safety and convenience rarely go together, but Apple does it well in iOS 12.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Apple</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><strong>Summary results</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Here is a summary of the winners for each section above:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Physical size:</strong> Tie on small phones; Samsung wins on the larger size</li><li><strong>Speed:</strong> Apple</li><li><strong>Screen quality:</strong> Tie</li><li><strong>Camera:</strong> Tie</li><li><strong>Home screen unlocking: </strong>Apple</li><li><strong>Storage capacity: </strong>Samsung</li><li><strong>Password management: </strong>Apple</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	<strong>And the overall winner:</strong>\n Both Samsung and Apple make great phones. Figure out which aspects of \nthe phone are more important to you and buy based on that personal \ncriteria. If you prefer Android, for example, go with Samsung. If the \nconvenience of Face ID matters more to you, then buy Apple.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 These phones will all serve your needs, and major apps will run on both Android and iOS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>A final note -- buy a case:</strong>\n All these devices are expensive, fragile, and easy to drop. I\'ve \ndropped phones in the past and you probably have too. After testing many\n cases over the years, I recommend the Speck <a href=\"https://www.speckproducts.com/apple/iphone-cases/iphone-x-cases/presidio-grip-iphone-x-cases/IPX-PR-GRIP.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"> Presidio Grip</a>. Not only do they protect the phone, but the grippy rubber really does help you hold tight without dropping.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Samsung vs. Apple', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '22-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-02-12 15:00:07', '2019-02-12 15:00:07', '', 22, 'http://localhost/Techthirstie/index.php/2019/02/12/22-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(32, 2, '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Comparison between Camera of Two leading mobile phone brands.</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	For most people taking casual snapshots, both Samsung and Apple offer <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-to-take-your-smartphone-photos-to-the-next-level/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">photo quality</a>\n that is good enough to replace a dedicated camera. That said, each \ncompany has strengths and weaknesses when it comes to photos and video.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n 	 	In general, Samsung\'s telephoto lens (these phones have two lenses, \none wide-angle and other for distance), while the new Apple phones have \nbetter dynamic range. However, in some cases, Apple\'s dynamic range \ncomes at the expense of flattening the visual tone and contrast of \nimages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 	This image, taken from a video created by <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WTg6ZYpvbo\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">SuperSaf TV</a>, demonstrates the importance of dynamic range. Note this image is part of a video test, but it shows off dynamic range nicely.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://zdnet4.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/2018/09/24/754bf1e1-4424-4be0-a698-7f40c7013ddf/c9ee0d97e37c2feaa0e4c9544b1ae796/dynamic-range.jpg\" alt=\"Dynamic range compared\" /><figcaption>Dynamic range compare - iPhone X Max vs Samsung Galaxy Note 9. Photo from <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WTg6ZYpvbo\">SuperSaf TV</a> on YouTube. </figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>\n		Featured stories\n	</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/top-cloud-providers-2019-aws-microsoft-azure-google-cloud-ibm-makes-hybrid-move-salesforce-dominates-saas/\">Top cloud providers 2019: AWS, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud; IBM makes hybrid move; Salesforce dominates SaaS</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/good-enough-5g-fixed-wireless-broadband-could-change-everything/\">Good enough 5G fixed-wireless broadband could change everything</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/russia-to-disconnect-from-the-internet-as-part-of-a-planned-test/\">Russia to disconnect from the internet as part of a planned test</a>\n                    </li><li>\n                        <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/an-apple-store-salesman-questioned-my-intelligence-says-customer/\">An Apple store salesman questioned my intelligence, says customer</a>\n                    </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 With the Samsung, \nthe sky is completely over-exposed with no cloud detail at all; the \nApple phone retains color in the trees, with less overall contrast, \nwhile the clouds are visible in the bright sky. Although it\'s not clear \nwhether Apple achieves this dynamic range with a better sensor or \nthrough more sophisticated manipulation of brightness curves, the iPhone\n XS is better.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 On the other hand, <a href=\"https://www.tomsguide.com/us/iphone-XS-vs-galaxy-note-9-camera,review-5766.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\"><em>Tom\'s Guide</em></a>\n took photos with the iPhone XS and Galaxy S9. The iPhone XS versions \nare flat and lifeless while the Note 9 photos are brighter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Portrait mode on these phones uses <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_photography\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">computational photography</a> techniques to adjust the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bokeh\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">bokeh</a>,\n or background blur, of photos. The resulting image, therefore, results \nfrom hardware capture together with software processing. As users, we \nonly care about the result, but it\'s helpful to be aware of what\'s \nhappening behind the scenes inside these devices.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Also: <a href=\"https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-the-iphone-lost-its-crown-to-the-apple-watch/\">How the iPhone lost its crown to the Apple Watch</a></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 The new iPhones include a larger <a href=\"https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+XS++and+XS+Max+Teardown/113021#s216143\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">sensor</a>\n that gathers light more effectively than in the past. As a result, the \nlow-light performance of the XS series has improved over the original \niPhone X. However, the Samsung devices have a larger <a href=\"https://www.androidauthority.com/what-is-aperture-789927/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">aperture</a>, so they allow more light into the sensor, which significantly improves photos taken in low light.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 If you want to see comparison photos, check this <a href=\"https://mashable.com/feature/apple-iphone-XS-max-review/#OpNvbMW7.aqy\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">article</a>, which does an excellent job showing side-by-side photos from Apple, Samsung, and Google flagship phones.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 Photo analyst Ken Rockwell has an excellent article praising the iPhone XS Max <a href=\"https://kenrockwell.com/tech/comparisons/iphone-vs-full-frame-bokeh.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">depth of field</a> and bokeh simulation while comparing it to a full-frame DSLR.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Summary:</strong>\n The iPhone XS offers significant camera improvement over last year\'s \niPhone X. However, the Samsung devices continue to hold their own. \nDepending on what you are photographing, either phone may give superior \nresults to the other, and you cannot go wrong either way.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> 	 <strong>Winner:</strong> Tie</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Samsung vs. Apple Camera Test', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'samsung-vs-apple', '', '', '2019-02-13 10:45:03', '2019-02-13 10:45:03', '', 0, 'http://localhost/Techthirstie/?p=32', 0, 'post', '', 4),
(33, 2, '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AAAsAsjAsasdbafsdjgfsdf</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Samsung vs. Apple', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '32-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '2019-02-12 15:04:54', '', 32, 'http://localhost/Techthirstie/index.php/2019/02/12/32-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
